@alchemicpunk1509 Sorry, but those two quotes are _not_ in any way similar.
First, "wer nicht arbeitet, soll auch nicht essen" is a (paraphrased) quote from the Bible, not "a rewording of a Nazi slogan".
Second, as far as I know, it has never been written on KZ doors mocking the inmates. "Arbeit macht frei" is usually avoided not because of its inherent meaning but because of how the Nazis twisted that meaning into something different. (A similar thing happened to "Jedem das Seine" which is also a much older quote that doesn't have any inherently "bad" meaning but got tainted by Nazi association.) Now, it certainly makes sense to criticise the thought behind the "essen" quote - but on its own, not because it may vaguely sound like something the Nazis could have said.

